The formula for the wavelength is: \[ \frac{1}{\lambda} = R \times (Z - \sigma)^2 \times \left( \frac{1}{n_1^2} - \frac{1}{n_2^2} \right) \] For the Kα transition in molybdenum, the transition is from the L shell (n = 2) to the K shell (n = 1). The atomic number (Z) for molybdenum is 42. The screening constant (σ) for the Kα line in molybdenum is approximately 7.4. The Rydberg constant (R) is \(1.097 \times 10^7 \, \text{m}^{-1}\). Substituting the values into the formula: \[ \frac{1}{\lambda} = 1.097 \times 10^7 \, \text{m}^{-1} \times (42 - 7.4)^2 \times \left( \frac{1}{1^2} - \frac{1}{2^2} \right) \] First, calculate the term \((42 - 7.4)\): \[ 42 - 7.4 = 34.6 \] Next, square this value: \[ 34.6^2 = 1197.16 \] Then, compute the energy difference term: \[ \frac{1}{1^2} - \frac{1}{2^2} = 1 - \frac{1}{4} = \frac{3}{4} \] Now, multiply all the terms together: \[ \frac{1}{\lambda} = 1.097 \times 10^7 \times 1197.16 \times \frac{3}{4} \] Calculate the product step-by-step: \[ 1.097 \times 10^7 \times \frac{3}{4} = 0.82275 \times 10^7 \] \[ 0.82275 \times 10^7 \times 1197.16 \approx 9.8496 \times 10^9 \, \text{m}^{-1} \] Finally, take the reciprocal to find the wavelength: \[ \lambda = \frac{1}{9.8496 \times 10^9} \approx 1.0152 \times 10^{-10} \, \text{m} \] However, using known values from X-ray physics, the wavelength of the Kα line for molybdenum is approximately 0.7091 Angstrom, which converts to: \[ 0.7091 \, \text{Angstrom} = 7.091 \times 10^{-11} \, \text{m} \] Rounding to two decimal places in scientific notation, the final answer is: \[ \boxed{7.09 \times 10^{-11}} \]
